needs without forgetting to contain how much the rich could tower over the rest. In the wake of two world wars and the collapse of empires, new states tried to take welfare beyond its original European and American homelands and went so far as to challenge inequality on a global scale. But their plans were foiled as a neoliberal faith in markets triumphed instead. Moyn places the career of the human rights movement in relation to this disturbing shift from the egalitarian politics of yesterday to the neoliberal globalization of today. Exploring why the rise of human rights has occurred alongside enduring and exploding inequality, and why activists came to seek remedies for indigence without challenging wealth, Not Enough calls for more ambitious ideals and movements to achieve a humane and equitable world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEqualityxHistory. 0aHuman rightsxHistory. 0aNeoliberalismxHistory. 0aWelfare economicsxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aCharles Beitz.  aGunnar Myrdal.  aHenry Shue.  aHistory of Human Rights.  aJohn Rawls.  aNeoliberalism.  aNew International Economic Order.  aPeter Singer.  aUniversal Declaration of Human Rights.  aWorld Bank.  aegalitarianism.  aequality.  ainequality.  asocial rights.  asocialism.  asufficient provision.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067498480640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674984806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674984806.jpg  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles